{{COI|date=November 2017}} {{Use British English|date=October 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}} {{Infobox Judge |honorific-prefix = |name = Nigel Richardson |honorific-suffix = |image = Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom (HM Government).svg |imagesize = 100px |caption = <small>[[Royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom]] |office = [[Deputy District Judge]] |term_start = March 2009 |term_end = |monarch = |predecessor = |successor = |office2 = |occupation = |profession = |term_start2 = |term_end2 = |birth_date = February 1958 |birth_place = |birthname = Nigel John Richardson<ref name="The Law Society"/> |nationality = British |spouse = |known_for = Representing victims of [[human rights]] abuses |residence = |alma_mater = [[Oxford University]] [[Master of Arts|MA]], [[London Guildhall University]]<ref name="“legal500"/> |website = [https://www.hja.net/legal-team/nigel-richardson/ www.hja.net] }}
'''Nigel John Richardson'''<ref name="The Law Society">{{cite web|title=The Law Society: Members|url=http://solicitors.lawsociety.org.uk/person/153392/nigel-john-richardson|publisher=The Law Society|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref> (born February 1958) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[human rights law|human rights]] lawyer who serves as a [[Deputy District Judge|deputy district judge]].<ref name="“thelawyer.com01"/> He was appointed to that office in May 2009. As a lawyer, Richardson is known for representing victims of human rights abuses in high profile criminal cases with international element.<ref name="solicitorsjournal01">{{cite web|title=A liberal and progressive parliamentary report on sex workers is heartening, says Nigel Richardson, but the criminal law needs to be clear and consistently enforced|url=https://www.solicitorsjournal.com/comment/progression-prostitution-laws-must-go-further|publisher=The Law Society|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref>
==Legal career== Richardson was educated at [[University of Oxford]] and [[London Guildhall University]].<ref name="HJA">{{cite web|title=HJA: Nigel Richardson|url=https://www.hja.net/legal-team/nigel-richardson/|publisher=HJA|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref> He was admitted as a [[solicitor]] in 1972.<ref name="chambers01">{{cite web|title=Chambers and Partners: Nigel Richardson|url=https://www.chambersandpartners.com/UK/person/9748/nigel-richardson|publisher=Chambers & Partnersr|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref> He became a trainee solicitor at [[Hodge Jones & Allen]] which specialises in human rights in 1985 and a senior partner in the firm in 1994.<ref name="HJA"/> In 2009 Richardson was appointed [[Deputy District Judge]] sitting in the [[Magistrates court]].<ref name="“thelawyer.com01">{{cite news |title=TheLawyer: The bar/bench appointments|url=https://www.thelawyer.com/issues/23-march-2009/people-115 |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref>
==Human rights== {{Rights}} ===Gay rights=== In 2012 Richardson acted for [[R v Peacock|Michael Peacock]] in a landmark [[obscenity]] trial which changed the law on [[Obscene Publications Act|obscene publications]] in this county<ref name="“gjss.org">{{cite news |title=R v Peacock: Landmark Trial Rede nes Obscenity Law |url=http://gjss.org/sites/default/files/issues/chapters/papers/Journal-10-01--04-Antoniou.pdf |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref> and was seen as a test of the [[Obscene Publications Act 1959]].<ref name="Hodgson">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/libertycentral/2012/jan/06/michael-peacock-obscenity-trial |title=Michael Peacock's acquittal is a victory for sexual freedom |publisher=''The Guardian'' |last1=Hodgson |first1=Nichi |accessdate= 9 September 2015 | date=6 January 2012}}</ref> Peacock, a male escort, was charged with six counts of distributing obscene DVDs under the [[Obscene Publications Act 1959]].<ref name="“bbc.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Not guilty verdict in DVD obscenity trial |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16443697 |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref> He was found not guilty by a jury at [[Southwark Crown Court]].<ref name="“solicitorsjournal.com02">{{cite news |title=Obscene publication acquittal prompts guidance review |url=https://www.solicitorsjournal.com/news/crime/general-principles/obscene-publication-acquittal-prompts-guidance-review |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref>
===Pornography=== In 2012, Richardson, together with his colleague [[Myles Jackman]], successfully defended [[Simon Walsh]], barrister and [[Greater London Assembly]] member who was accused of possession of [[extreme pornography]] under [[Section 63 of the Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008#2012 test case|Section 63 of the Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008]]. The case came as a test to the Act.<ref name="“standard.co.uk06">{{cite news |title=Simon Walsh: How bodged arrest and 'profoundly damaging' false charges have ruined my City Hall career|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/simon-walsh-how-bodged-arrest-and-profoundly-damaging-false-charges-have-ruined-my-city-hall-career-8046087.html |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref>
===Racism=== In 2016 Richardson represented [[Coronation Street]] actor Marc Anwar<ref name="“independent06">{{cite news |title=Marc Anwar sacked from Coronation Street over ‘racially offensive tweets’ |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/marc-anwar-coronation-street-sacked-racially-offensive-tweets-twitter-a7328786.html |accessdate=11 November 2017 |date=11 November 2017}}</ref> who became the centre of a racism row after posting a controversial comment about Indians on [[Twitter]], which resulted in his sacking from the ITV soap.<ref name="“standard.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Coronation Street star Marc Anwar SACKED from soap after astonishing racist Twitter attack |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/coronation-street-actor-marc-anwar-8909333.amp |accessdate=11 November 2017 |date=11 November 2017}}</ref>
===Joe Orton's retrial=== As a judge, Richardson presided over [[Joe Orton]]'s retrial in 2012.<ref name="“camdennewjournal.com">{{cite news |title=Camden Journal: Orton and Halliwell back in the dock |url=http://archive.camdennewjournal.com/orton-and-halliwell-back-dock5 |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref> Orton was an English writer who in 1962 was sentenced to six months imprisonment for historic sexual offences and fined for stealing and damaging Islington Public Library books.<ref name="“islingtongazette.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Joe Orton retrial |url=http://www.islingtongazette.co.uk/news/heritage/tragic-islington-playwright-joe-orton-escapes-jail-50-years-later-1-1194984 |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref> Prosecution insisted on retrial fifty years after he served his conviction.<ref name="“islingtontribune.com">{{cite news |title=Simulated retrial sees playwright Joe Orton escape jail |url=https://archive.islingtontribune.com/news/2012/feb/simulated-retrial-sees-playwright-joe-orton-escape-jail |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref> The case made national headlines with newspapers arguing as to whether it was right to put Orton on trial. Orton later suggested that the lengthy sentence was given because “he was a queer.”<ref name="“dailymail.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Why I blame myself for the murder of Sixties playwright Joe Orton, by theatre critic and friend Michael Thornton |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1167197/Why-I-blame-murder-Sixties-playwright-Joe-Orton-theatre-critic-friend-Michael-Thornton.html |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref>
==Academic career and publications== Richardson was a visiting criminal law lecturer of [[Oxford Institute of Legal Practice]] from 2001, until its closure in 2013.<ref name="“studentprobono">{{cite news |title=Student Pro Bono: About Us |url=http://www.studentprobono.net/aboutus.php|accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref> In 2014, together with Peter Clark, barrister at 187 Fleet Street Chambers<ref name="“gregfoxsmith.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Book Review: Sexual Offences- a Practitioners Guide (Richardson/Clark) |url=http://www.gregfoxsmith.co.uk/?p=1538|accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref> who specialises in sex cases, he co-authored a book called ''Sexual Offences – A Practitioner’s Guide.''<ref name="“bloomsburylawonline">{{cite news |title=Richardson and Clark: Sexual Offences A Practitioner's Guide |url=http://www.bloomsburylawonline.com/2014/06/30/richardson-and-clark-sexual-offences-a-practitioners-guide-press-release/ |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref><ref name="“bloomsburyprofessional">{{cite news |title=Sexual Offences A Practitioner's Guide by Richardson and Clark |url=https://www.bloomsburyprofessional.com/uk/richardson-and-clark-sexual-offences-a-practitioners-guide-9781780433271/ |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref> Richardson also co-authored ''Blackstones Guide to the Human Rights Act 2000''.<ref name="“legal500">{{cite news |title=legal 500: Nigel Richardson |url=http://www.legal500.com/firms/1597/offices/248/lawyers/60189 |accessdate=22 October 2017 |date=22 October 2017}}</ref>
==Charity== Richardson is a trustee of [[English Collective of Prostitutes]], a charity which aims to transform the lives of sex workers by campaigning against decriminalisation of prostitution and provides information, help, and support to individual sex workers and others who are concerned with sex workers' [[human rights|human]], [[civil rights|civil]], legal, and economic rights.<ref name="theguardian05">{{cite web|title=Call for change in law to protect prostitutes from violent crime|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/jan/16/change-law-prostitutes-crime-violent|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref>
